\begin_layout Standard
We start with describing the interaction between a non-relativistic electronic
 system and an electromagnetic (EM) field using quantum electrodynamics
 in the Coulomb gauge.
 We consider the Hamiltonian in a multipolar form rigorously equivalent
 to the standard description, so-called Power-Zienau-Woolley Hamiltonian
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "power_coulomb_1959,atkins_interaction_1970,cohen-tannoudji_photons_1997"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}\widehat{H}_{PZW}= & \widehat{H}_{s}+\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\left\{ \frac{1}{2\epsilon_{0}}\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\left(\mathbf{\nabla}\times\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right)^{2}\right\} \\
 & -\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\cdot\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)+\frac{1}{2\epsilon_{0}}\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\left|\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right|^{2}.
\end{split}
\label{eq:Power-Zienau-Woolley}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the vector potential of the EM field and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the transverse field displacement, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=\epsilon_{0}\widehat{\mathbf{E}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)+\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the Hamiltonian of the matter system and will be specified in the following.
 Here we ignore the multipolar magnetization coupling.
 We assume the polarization operator of the matter only has transverse contribut
ion to the EM field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 And we consider a globally neutral system, so that the displacement is
 only a transverse field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=\widehat{\mathbf{D}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

, and we will drop the 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp$
\end_inset

 notation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For quantum electrodynamics in the Coulomb gauge, the operator associated
 with the vector potential is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=i\sum_{\mathbf{k}}\frac{{\cal E}_{\mathbf{k}}}{\omega_{\mathbf{k}}}\mathbf{e}_{\mathbf{k}}\left(\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}+\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}e^{-i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal E}_{\mathbf{k}}=\sqrt{\frac{\hbar\omega_{\mathbf{k}}}{2\epsilon_{0}L^{n}}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the volume of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensonal space and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathbf{k}}=c\left|\mathbf{k}\right|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 are destruction and creation operators of the field and satisfying the
 commutation relations: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}},\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k^{\prime}}}^{\dagger}\right]=\delta\left(\mathbf{k}-\mathbf{k^{\prime}}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 and The electric and magnetic fields can be obtained according to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\widehat{\mathbf{B}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right) & = & \mathbf{\boldsymbol{\nabla}}\times\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=i\sum_{\mathbf{k}}\frac{{\cal E}_{\mathbf{k}}}{c}\mathbf{k}\times\mathbf{e}_{\mathbf{k}}\left(\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}-\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}e^{-i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}\right),\label{eq:B_operator}\\
\widehat{\mathbf{E}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right) & = & -\frac{1}{c}\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=i\sum_{\mathbf{k}}{\cal E}_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{e}_{\mathbf{k}}\left(\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}-\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}e^{-i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}\right),\label{eq:E_operator}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\boldsymbol{\nabla}}\cdot\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 in the Coulomb gauge.
 The transverse Hamiltonian of the EM field can be represented as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}\widehat{H}_{R}= & \int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\left\{ \frac{\epsilon_{0}}{2}\widehat{\mathbf{E}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\widehat{\mathbf{B}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)^{2}\right\} \\
= & \sum_{\mathbf{k}}\hbar\omega_{\mathbf{k}}\left(\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}+\frac{1}{2}\right)
\end{split}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\widehat{B}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{E}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 are pure EM field operators, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a mixed operator of electronic and field degrees of freedom.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several advantages to take Power-Zienau-Woolley Hamiltonian in
 this form as the starting point.
 First, the electron–radiation coupling can be expressed in terms of electric
 field and polarization, instead of vector potentials.
 The effect of the electronic system toward the EM field is included within
 the polarization distribution.
 The electric dipole Hamiltonian, a widely used form for studying light-matter
 interaction, emerges easily after long-wavelength approximation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cohen-tannoudji_photons_1997"

\end_inset

.
 Second, the displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 is formally the momentum conjugate with the vector potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 satisfying the canonical commutation relation, 
\begin_inset Formula $[\widehat{\mathbf{D}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right),\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\right)]=i\hbar\delta\left(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We will see in the following that it is crucial that the Hamiltonian in
 terms of canonical conjugate variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Electric Dipole Hamiltonian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, we consider an electronic system with a spatial distribution
 of the order of Bohr radius interacting with an EM field of wavelength
 much larger than the size of the system.
 In this case, we can exploit the long-wavelength approximation to get the
 electric dipole Hamiltonian after generalized Göppert-Mayer transformation
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cohen-tannoudji_photons_1997"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
c.f.
 Cohen p.
 304-312
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{ED}=\widehat{H}_{s}-\widehat{\mathbf{d}}\cdot\widehat{\mathbf{E}}\left(0\right)+\sum_{\mathbf{k}}\hbar\omega_{\mathbf{k}}\left(\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}+\frac{1}{2}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so-called the electric dipole Hamiltonian.
 In this representation, the interaction is simply described by a coupling
 term between the dipole moment 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\widehat{\mathbf{d}}}=\sum_{\alpha}q_{\alpha}\mathbf{\widehat{\mathbf{r}}}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and the electric field evaluated at the position of the system.
 We assume the electronic system is located at the origin.
 The advantage of the electric dipole Hamiltonian is that the coupling is
 linear in terms of field operator.
 The electric dipole Hamiltonian is usually taken as a starting point to
 study quantum optical effects, such as spontaneous emission.
\end_layout

