\begin_layout Standard
Spontaneous emission is an irreversible process that a quantum system transition
s from an excited state to a ground state and emits photons with a random
 phase and direction.
 Spontaneous emission is considered a quantum optical effect of fundamental
 importance for phenomena such as luminescence, fluorescence, and phosphorescenc
e, which cannot be explained by classical electromagnetic theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a review of quantum electrodynamics description for spontaneous emission,
 we consider a simple model of two-level system 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{s}=\varepsilon_{0}\left|0\right\rangle \left\langle 0\right|+\varepsilon_{1}\left|1\right\rangle \left\langle 1\right|
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which only coupled via the interaction with the EM field.
 We assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}<\varepsilon_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=\varepsilon_{1}-\varepsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The electronic dipole moment operator takes the form of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathbf{d}}=\boldsymbol{\mu}_{01}\left(\left|0\right\rangle \left\langle 1\right|+\left|1\right\rangle \left\langle 0\right|\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mu}_{01}=\left\langle 0\right|\sum_{\alpha}q_{\alpha}\mathbf{\widehat{\mathbf{r}}}_{\alpha}\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is the transition dipole moment of the two states.
