\end_layout

\end_inset

Apart from the detail balance concerns, Ehrenfest dynamics has some deficiencies
 of capturing quantum effects, such as spontaneous and stimulated emission
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "li_mixed_2018"

\end_inset

.
 It has been shown that, Ehrenfest dynamics is capable of partially capturing
 quantum effects in quantitative sense.
 Yet, the deficiencies become qualitative failures in some cases.
 Specifically, consider a spontaneous emission situation where the electronic
 system has zero averaged current (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{J}=0$
\end_inset

) intially and within a vaccum environment (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}=\mathbf{B}=0$
\end_inset

) without external fields, the electron–radiation coupling stay zero along
 the propagation, so that Ehrenfest dynamics fail to predict any spontaneous
 emission in this case.
 Namely, the mean-field nature of Ehrenfest dynamics may cause unphysical
 results.
\end_layout

