\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
What is Raman?
\end_layout

\end_inset

Raman scattering is an inelastic scattering of the incident photons by a
 molecule excited to higher vibrational levels, results in a small fraction
 of the scattered photons having a energy shift in spectra.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
What's Resonance Raman?
\end_layout

\end_inset

When the incident photon align the molecular excitation frequencies, Raman
 scattering exhibit a resonance enhancement in spectra.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
coupled to vib
\end_layout

\end_inset

To address the scattering process, we consider a molecular system with the
 ground state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|g\nu_{1}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and the excited state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|e\nu_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 coupled to the vibrational modes, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Raman scattering is a second order process.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
scattering process
\end_layout

\end_inset

In the presence of the incident photon at frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{I}$
\end_inset

 that line up with the excitation energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{I}=E_{e\nu_{2}}-E_{g\nu_{1}}$
\end_inset

, the molecular system is excited by photon absorption.
 Then, the excited molecule emits a photon with energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{S}=E_{e\nu_{2}}-E_{g\nu_{1}^{\prime}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Raman and Rayleigh
\end_layout

\end_inset

Raman scattering happens if the process is inelastic (
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}\neq v_{1}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{I}\neq\omega_{S}$
\end_inset

), otherwise the process is Rayleigh scattering if 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}=v_{1}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{I}=\omega_{S}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

