\begin_layout Standard
In order to study the steady state of non-equilibrium dynamics, we introduce
 a non-radiative dissipation among the vibrational modes of the ground state.
 We know that, in absence of the external CW field, the ground state population
 of different vibrational modes should follow Boltzmann distribution and
 the dissipative transition rate must be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\overline{\rho_{00}}}{\overline{\rho_{11}}}=\frac{\gamma_{0\leftarrow1}}{\gamma_{1\leftarrow0}}=\frac{e^{-\beta\varepsilon_{0}}}{e^{-\beta\varepsilon_{1}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1/kT$
\end_inset

 is the temperature of the molecule.
 Then, we can express the dissipation rates to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{0\leftarrow1}=\gamma_{\mathrm{vib}}e^{-\beta\varepsilon_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1\leftarrow0}=\gamma_{\mathrm{vib}}e^{-\beta\varepsilon_{2}}$
\end_inset

 in terms of an empirical parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\mathrm{vib}}$
\end_inset

.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\mathrm{vib}}$
\end_inset

 should be related to the electron–vibration coupling strength, which determine
 how fast the vibrational modes of the molecule reach equilibrium.
 With this dissipative transition between 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|1\right\rangle $
